                "href": "/profile/Tyler-Cook"
            },
            "answer_text": "Some might, but they shouldn't. I have slave owners down one branch of my family tree and abolitionists down another.  I'm even related to Lincoln's law partner who claims to have helped alter the President's opinion on slavery, but I am no more responsible for the emancipation then I am for the practice of slavery in the first place.  I don't believe in original sin or collective guilt or that responsibility for ancestral crimes are somehow magically transferred through the bloodline.  There is no reason to be ashamed for another person's crime.   Although there have been multiple shameful events in American history which supposedly compromise our supposed moral authority, most happened under false narratives or in secret.  So, how responsible are deceased Americans? The only thing I feel is frustration for being forced to deal with someone else's past mistakes while being almost completely powerless to affect change in the present. ",
