                "name": "Thomas L. Johnson",
                "href": "/profile/Thomas-L-Johnson-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "Certainly not more than the Germans, Brits, and Australians feel about their histories. As a member of an immigrant community that has been in this country for about 150 years, I feel particular pride in the USA despite the obvious missteps that any country makes during an existence of a quarter millennium.   In most respects, the US has exemplified a country that was founded on optimistic principles of the Enlightenment combined with some of the worst practices of the European colonizers, most terrible of which was slavery.  It did not invent it but certainly retained it long after the recognition of its indefensibility.With regards to native populations, the early Americans were like the early Australians or Argentinians, bristling with the desire to add new lands to the county even while forcing the aboriginal populations into reserves.   If we had never addressed these terrible issues, we would deserve whatever shame might befall us.   African- and native-Americans are Americans to a degree that north African immigrant communites in France or Turkish minorities in Germany have never become.  I went to an American baseball game with a German friend in the last week and she was surprised to see black and Latino fans singing the national anthem along with the Caucasians.  When asked, I said that they are just as American as anyone.  She was surprised by my comment as it is not the normal state of affairs in much of the EU. There is a past that includes many shameful realities; but the shame does not characterize the USA. ",
