            "author_info": {
                "name": "Mike Holovacs",
                "href": "/profile/Mike-Holovacs"
            },
            "answer_text": "Some do and some don't.  There are generally two types of shame among Americans.  One type of shame is the idea that past wrongs must be made right with financial incentive or legal relief for a current generation despite the sins of the past. Think about the camp who advocates for financial reparations for slavery, paid to descendants. Partisanship aside, I have found shame tied to money to be a phenomenon found on the more leftward side of the American political spectrum. This goes hand in hand with their paternalistic outlook toward minorities. Then there's the type of shame where the person admits that something was done wrong and moves on with life. Am I ashamed of how this country treated the American Indian? Absolutely. Was it wrong? Yes. Do I want to create government debt to make it right? No. Admission of the wrongdoing and an apology is good enough for most people, especially if societal-level change has come about. My own opinion is that this school of thought is more right of center, but I will no doubt get flak for this thinking. ",
